          "title": "The four-verb verdict — God dismantles the mighty man",
          "body": "At verse 5 the psalm's grammar shifts from accusation to divine verdict, and the shift is total. Four destruction-verbs cascade without pause: God will break down (natats — to demolish, as a wall is demolished), snatch up (chatah — to seize, to scoop away), tear away (nasach — to pull up by the roots), and uproot (sharash — the verb used of uprooting a tree at its root system). The verbs are not accidental or ornamental — each names a different dimension of removal. Natats is structural collapse. Chatah is sudden seizure. Nasach is violent displacement. Sharash is the extirpation of the root itself. Nothing remains. The mighty man will be removed from his tent (ohel — his earthly security, his household establishment) and from the land of the living (the realm of historical existence). His power, his reputation, his legacy — all of it gone. The Selah after verse 5 demands that the reader sit with each verb and feel the totality of the verdict before moving to the witness scene that follows."
