          "body": "Verses 6-7 call the righteous community as a witness-gallery to God's judgment. They will 'see and fear' (52:6) — the sight of the mighty man's collapse produces not satisfaction alone but reverent awe (yare), the recognition that a moral order governs history and that God enforces it. Then they will laugh (sachaq, 52:6). This is not the petty laughter of schadenfreude; it is the eschatological laughter of those who believed God's word and watched it prove true (compare Psalm 2:4, where God Himself laughs at those who oppose His purposes, and Psalm 37:13). The taunt they speak (52:7) is a careful theological autopsy: the mighty man failed at the one decisive choice — he would not make God his refuge (maoz — stronghold, place of safety). Instead he trusted in riches (osher) and was strong in havvah (destructive desire, ruin). He chose to be strong in what destroys rather than in what saves. The righteous laughter is the Psalter's way of saying that the universe is not morally neutral — that evil which boasts will one day be the object of derision, and that God's word will be vindicated before witnesses."
