        "body": "The pivot from accusation to verdict is one of the most forceful 'but' constructions in the Psalter. 'But God (gam el)...' — not 'but eventually' or 'but in a better world,' but God, the actor, the sovereign. The verse delivers four verbs of divine judgment in rapid succession, and the sequencing matters: natats (demolish structurally) → chatah (seize suddenly) → nasach (tear away violently) → sharash (uproot at the root system). The verbs move from broad structural collapse to increasingly specific forms of removal, ending at the root — the thing that would allow regrowth. When God uproots (sharash), He leaves no possibility of recovery from that root.\n\nThe object of each verb is the mighty man's established position in the world: his tent (ohel — household, inheritance, earthly security), his place among the living (erets chayim — the land of the living, present historical existence). The judgment is total removal from both the social and the biological realms. The Selah that follows demands a pause here — the reader is to hear each verb separately before moving on.\n\nThis is not a prayer for vengeance but a theological declaration. Peter Davids (NIGTC on James) and Douglas Moo (Pillar NTC) both observe in their treatments of New Testament wisdom literature that the Psalter's imprecatory and judgment sections function as affirmations of God's moral governance of history — they are the believer's means of refusing to take personal vengeance (Psalm 37:1-2; Romans 12:19) while nonetheless affirming that evil does not go unaddressed. The psalmist does not pick up a sword; he declares what God will do and leaves it there.\n\nThe temporal marker 'forever' (netsach) is the verse's theological weight-bearing term. Netsach is used in the Psalms for both God's eternal purposes (Psalm 44:23) and for irreversible judgments. Here it marks the finality of the removal. This is not a temporary setback for the mighty man — it is permanent exclusion. The tree is not trimmed; it is uprooted.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Natats* (break down) is used of demolishing walls, altars, and structures. *Chatah* (snatch up) appears in the context of scooping coals from a fire — a sudden, complete seizure. *Nasach* (tear away) is the violent pulling-up of tent pegs. *Sharash* (uproot) is specifically the destruction of the root system — compare Amos 2:9 where God destroys the Amorites 'from above' and their roots 'from below.'"
