        "body": "Verses 6-7 introduce the righteous (tsaddiqim) as a community of witnesses to the divine verdict. Their response is a triad: they see, they fear, they laugh. Each verb requires careful attention. To 'see' is to bear witness — the righteous do not turn away from God's judgment but watch it and learn from it. To 'fear' (yare) is to respond with the reverent awe that the sight of God's moral order being enforced properly produces in those who believe — this is not terror but the holy recognition that God's word has proven true. And to 'laugh' (sachaq) is to enter into the eschatological vindication that God's judgment accomplishes.\n\nThe laughter of the righteous in the Psalms is consistently the laughter of those who believed God against all appearances and watched His word prevail (Psalm 2:4; 37:13). It is the laughter Sarah laughed when Isaac was born — the laughter of the impossible having come to pass. It is not cruelty but vindication. John Calvin, commenting on verse 6, distinguishes carefully between the malicious joy that rejoices in a neighbor's calamity and the godly joy that 'arises from the vindication of God's glory and the triumph of His truth.' The righteous laugh not at the person but at the collapse of the system of lies.\n\nThe taunt of verse 7 is a theological autopsy — 'Behold the man who would not make God his refuge.' The word for 'would not' is a volitional negative — he chose not to, he refused. This is not ignorance but decision. He had the option of making God his maoz (stronghold, fortress) and chose instead to trust in the abundance of his riches (osher — wealth) and to be strong in his havvah (destructive desire, ruin). The autopsy makes the irony explicit: he chose to be strong in the very thing that destroyed him.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Maoz* (refuge, stronghold) is the same word used in Psalm 27:1 ('the LORD is the stronghold of my life') and Nahum 1:7 ('the LORD is good, a stronghold in the day of trouble'). *Sachaq* (laugh) is the verb of the laughter of vindication throughout the Psalter and wisdom literature — not frivolous but weighted with theological significance."
